Well, my memory of flea markets is they were like a covered-over yard sale. Half the stalls were people with knock-off goods, or bins full of miscellaneous stuff that you had to dig through.
There was the produce section (these days I'd guess we call that a farmer's market), the tech area (three dollar watches that had been doctored to seem waterproof, or second-hand TVs), the clothing area (two thousand units of the current meme corporate character), and the randomly spaced double stalls run by crotchety old guys with several thousand vinyl records or books. And let's not forget the shifty-eyed redneck with an armory spread over the tables ... and no questions asked.
Back then Nazi memorabilia was sold openly. Ohh, there were fights and a few shootings. Correction: accidents.
So remember contemporary 80s stuff (Spuds McKenzie, Transformers, the MTV aesthetic translated to a pole-barned parking lot) mixed with the backwoods versions of magic users that crawled out for Saturday & Sunday. They're part carnival hawker, part fallen-on-hard-times, part the guy that a hardboiled PI would keep as an information source.
